metadata.name: Differential Threads #2
metadata.description:
Cracks, whales, butterflies, ghosts, birds.
A person leaning forward and a couple of raindrops.

I‚Äôve seen many familiar shapes while working on ‚ÄòDifferential Threads‚Äô.

Now I think of them as a sort of sketchpad for future series, snapshots from a journey in search of elusive shapes and new textures,  bound together by a fine thread of open ended experimentation.

By creating an array of coordinates based on a few rules and constrained by width and height, each pair of points gets subdivided, smoothed and then turned into a drawing path. 
The texture is achieved by repeating and offsetting multiple lines drawn across the surface and following random x and y axis.

pressing [s] saves a png in current resolution

[2] changes resolution to 4800x4800px

[3]  7200x7200px

[4]  9600x9600px

[5]  12000x12000px

[6]  14400x14400px

[1]  reverts to original size 2400x2400px

‚ÄòDifferential Threads‚Äô was written in plain js, based on sketches that I did while taking [notochord.xyz](http://notochord.xyz) classes on generative design and agent simulations. Some of the concepts were inspired by Matt Perkin‚Äôs (@nudoru) write up on ‚Äúcreating interesting paths‚Äù and Tyler Hobb‚Äôs essay on generative brushes.

It may take some prolonged time to perform the drawing at high resolutions
It loads a little faster in Chrome but was tested on Safari and Firefox.

metadata.name: Reflector #61
metadata.description:
REFLECTOR is an exploration of reflecting rays of light in two-dimensions by Juhani Halkom√§ki.

The pieces consist of 100 to 1200 rays of light that bounce two times when colliding with an object or the edge of the canvas. Some may seem more beautiful than others but they all have the same internals.

---
Features info
---

Dark mode - Paint the background black
Monochrome - No colors just grays
Emitter mode - One of the following: EDGE, SHAPE, POINT, GRID

Number Of Shapes - How many shapes are on the scene (1-4)
Number of Rays - How many rays are emitted (100-1000)
Number of Bounces - How many times the rays bounce (2-3)
Ray spreading - How much the ray angles are spread (10-100)

Color mode - Either SMOOTH or STEPS
Color spectrum size - How wide hue spectrum is used
Color spectrum offset - How much the hue is offset
Color step interval - How many consecutive rays should have the same color
Color step count - How many steps is the color spectrum divided into

metadata.name: Dencity #582
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Impressions of Order #104
metadata.description:
‚ÄòImpressions of Order‚Äô is a collection of 300 generative compositions. 

Inspired by 90s ROM cartridges, server farms and future cityscapes this project explores perception and documentation of ‚Äòorder‚Äô within complex systems. 

--------------------------------------------------------

This artwork is best enjoyed in high-resolution so that the subtle layering, colour shifts, variation in hard and soft edges, faint impressions of construction, and the various low-probability glitchy events can be fully appreciated. 

By default, the artwork will load in 2K resolution (1400 x 2000 px). It is recommended that you view the work in 4K or 6K to appreciate the finer details. 

The keyboard buttons: ‚Äú2‚Äù, ‚Äú4‚Äù, and ‚Äú6‚Äù can be pressed to change the resolution to 2K, 4K and 6K resolution accordingly. 

To download an image at its current resolution, press the keyboard button ‚ÄúS‚Äù.

metadata.name: Eucalyptus and Sagebrush #184
metadata.description:
Eucalyptus and Sagebrush is inspired by the eucalyptus trees and sagebrush found in California. These plants, and the hills they inhabit, have long been a source of beauty and adventure in my life, and I find myself repeatedly drawn back to them. The sunsets in coastal California are a perfect compliment to these hills, and I set out to represent that combination in this work.

Each iteration of this algorithm feels, to me, like a glimpse out of a car window on a drive up the coast, a pause on a cool morning hike, or a memory of tearing through sharp underbrush with good company.

Stylistically and texturally, I drew from landscapes rendered in oil pastels, placing thousands of tiny circles, alluding to the effect of depositing particles of color onto paper. 

I hope that this work evokes in the viewer the feelings of peace, wildness, and adventure that I feel when I watch the sun set over these hills.

Nat Sarkissian


Notes:

metadata.name: Zug #196
metadata.description:
Zug is the German word for train, but it also translates to 'a force that pulls in a specific direction' which feels very fitting, though it might remain unclear in which direction exactly.

The image is build layering around 9000 transparent strokes grouped so that the resemblance of a passing train is created. Most strokes are blurred, some are repeating.

All editions share the same base color palette. From it three different palettes are derived for the light, medium and dark colors. Press 'c' to get a better idea of how this works.

Initial sketch made for the Weekly Creative Coding Challenge hosted by Rapha√´l de Courville (@Sableraph).

Commands:
f = fullscreen toggle
b = change window background color
c = color palettes overlay toggle
s = save image at 1080 x 1920 pixels
p = save image at 3240 x 5760 pixels

metadata.name: Pixel Management #838
metadata.description:
#tezpole has demonstrated to us all the importance of effective Cable Management. Intrigued by this challenge, I've delved deep into the pixels of this issue. üôÇ

Drawing inspiration from Rev Dan Catt‚Äôs 'Tally!' and applying similar principles of Cable Management, I've assembled a fun and free OE project.

This project dynamically evolves with each iteration.Grid is determined by a random value calculated as follows: the lower bound starts at 3 and increases incrementally with every 100 iterations, while the upper bound starts at 4 and increases with every 30 iterations. In practical terms, as the iteration count increases, both the minimum and maximum possible number of cols&rows gradually increase.

3200x3200px
Press [s] for .jpeg | Press [p] for .png
Made with p5.js

Rob Scalera | 2023

metadata.name: Fictional Day #3
metadata.description:
"Fictional Day" is an art collection that captures a year in the life of an artist living in a fictional world, through 365 pieces representing each day. Each piece reflects their emotions and experiences, as they navigate their daily life, in this fictional world, with fictional friends, family and society. The collection offers a window into the artist's mind, showcasing the beauty and potential of both reality and fiction.

metadata.name: Round Round #80
metadata.description:
Primarily I focused on using circles as the main element in creating compositions. It involves arranging, manipulating and combining circles to form different shapes, patterns and designs.
Here, concepts such as symmetry, balance, rhythm and repetition are often examined. I used circles of different sizes, colors, textures, and opacity to create depth and visual interest, and added compositions like squiggly lines for complexity and variety.
The possibilities are endless when it comes to circles, as they have the freedom to experiment with different techniques and styles. It can take many forms including minimal, abstract designs, mandalas (spiritual symbols), optical illusions or even representational images made entirely of circles.
By focusing on the simplicity and versatility of circles, I have created a visual approach that evokes harmony, unity, and balance while also allowing for creative expression.

Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Rapport #109
metadata.description:
The concept of nexus is a powerful one. It speaks to the idea that everything is related and that each part is necessary to create the whole. Rapport is about the relationship these parts have, harmonious or discordant, to convey a sense of unity and purpose. You are invited to explore the details and interactions of each object in its surroundings, recognizing the immense value they all have in building greater things.

metadata.name: Dialog Box #236
metadata.description:
Dialog Box is a playful generative art project that invites viewers to engage with the concept of choice in the digital age. Inspired by the early Mac OS, the artwork presents an interface of two buttons, each symbolizing a choice steeped in 80s and 90s pop culture, from the serious to the lighthearted.
